Food is to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, the growth rate was higher than expected in November – after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3%, Bloomberg said.
In contrast to the U.S., British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the lead interest rate. In its discretion, the lowering of interest rates would favor rising commodity prices and a slight drop in unemployment to the emergence of an inflation spiral.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the Zwickmühle: “We have to ‘dismiss’ inflation in order to exclude the need for action at a later stage.
At 3.3 percent, the rate of inflation reached a twelve-year high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone is due to rising food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat listings increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose this year by 52 percent - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, although it is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
Analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate for the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
Experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice for 2008.
Gallup spots government crisis
After long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while the approval for the socialists, according to Gallup, has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent.
The difference among partisan voters is clear thanks to the high determination of opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) are in favor of a fifth (20 percent) of the MSZP.
According to a survey, MDF and SZDSZ are under the parliamentary entrance barrier: they reach 2% in the total population.
The number of party voters has increased by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low, the overall economic atmosphere has deteriorated further – never before was the proportion of those who judge the country’s economic situation as “extremely poor” so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent think it is “fairly poor.”
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only one-tenth is expected to improve.
A Gallup survey conducted in December found that 71% of respondents — a historic high — judged the Prime Minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents generally have great confidence or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while the share of advocates for Viktor Orbán makes up 38 percent.
Approximately 54% do not trust the leader at all, compared to 27% distrust against the leader of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of the political mood is the number of those who think you could get control of the dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister even without a change of government.
After the unrest last October, 35% had voted in favour of the remainder of the government and the leader, this share is now only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent responded that they would "securely" participate, and another 20 percent would "probably" vote.
For comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place on Sunday, only 55% would go to the polls "with certainty" and another 15% would consider their participation to be "probable".
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% would vote against practice fees, and 84% would vote against hospital daily fees.
Translated to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the proportions of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would even be 81, 84, and 89 percent, respectively.
