Many places are saved on disinfectants
More than a thousand infections have been reported in hospitals this year due to improper antibiotic treatment.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overoccupation of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that do not help to curb infections, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The injured in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. A major surgery could not be done since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
By 10 December of this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark number is likely to be higher.
Approximately two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the means are dosed too high or misused, antibiotic-resistant bacteria that are well-responding will result in rapid spread to hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the daily hospital.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the necessary antibiotics for the treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable to curb the formation or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, the hospitals should examine the induced patients and immediately isolate MRSA infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not so frequently practiced in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies on the part of the state health insurance fund for this examination.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the remedy can develop, but this directive is not always followed by hospitals.
Among the outpatient or primary care patients, microbiological sampling is even less common, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Saved in disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted by nurses from one patient to another.
This is why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks are of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in local hospitals.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds lined close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, it even occurs in less well-established financial hospitals that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that favor the development of infections.
Such infections have been shown to be far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are complied with, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Getting under control of MRSA infections causes health insurance enormous costs, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Center for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of multiresistant pathogens (including MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals.
