Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Minister of Finance János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements worth EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a €300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects undertaken with subsidies from the Cohesion Fund. The loan contract of €100 million was signed earlier, the current agreement deals with the use of the €200 million granted.
The €150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has allocated a total of EUR 300 million to Hungary for this purpose; the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided on later as part of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the area of innovation, the contracting partners have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will be mainly invested in research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also addressed.
It was agreed that as soon as Hungary has clarified the details of subway financing with the EU, the original contract and any amendments will be re-debated.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest rates are EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferment of 8 years, free of provisions.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all over Europe looks closely at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who still buys the cheapest market in the EU, but is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most coveted pavement for real estate purchases in the Eastern European region, with affordable ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar are the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later also attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the very cheap area of Russia has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers enticing offers - trading and office spaces offer the highest yields.
Bulgaria is on the best path to become one of the most attractive European golf paradises, and thus attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons, as well as the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in large-scale fashion, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people purchasing real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are predominantly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle buy either revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or fallen homes for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication options are great, but also the proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are crucial for buyers.
The second category includes those looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of medium to long-term value increase.
Real estate in the capital, however, is becoming constantly more expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been an increase of 21% annually.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are consulting on the Bali roadmap, which sets out emissions-reducing measures for the post-2012 period, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
Currently, there is a heavy debate between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether the developed countries are willing, in addition to reducing emissions, to support developing countries both financially and technologically.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member council, which is expected to be reviewed by the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as read in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that by 2020, the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (measured to 1990 levels), whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be successfully reached. The Union would even be prepared to advocate for a 30 percent reduction, provided other large industrialized countries in the world, or developing countries, are also prepared to comply with their obligations as they can and are responsible.
Gábor Fodor emphasized that the objective of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, while the EU and its then 15 member states had already committed to a reduction of 8%.
The benchmark for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a benchmark that the country will fulfill, as read in the Environment Ministry's press release.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific committee on climate change, which was recently awarded by the UN.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and the rise of the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, resulting in extremely serious and irreparable consequences according to scientists.
British Army Advertises on YouTube
British army units have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to increase popularity on the video portal.
Initially, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban online since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The images shot with miniature cameras attached to helmets are checked at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and subsequently sent to London, where they are put on the Internet.
The inevitable political message
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such shots, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
Publicized propaganda of this kind is almost free compared to conventional television advertising, defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message as they confirm the right to exist of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur footage, which, in addition to the carefully processed, censored footage, also put it on the net - such as those that show the deaths of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are spoken at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, from the scenes of war in Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos shot in use have already been loaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the freely downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-saving simulation.
