Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk poses the "exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term."
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which presumably aims to provoke such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is considered a failure by political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition."
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor limbs, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "have severely damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously booming, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called "national self-defense associations" have been founded.
"These groups are common in defining themselves as a civilian organization, while openly boasting about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (catastrophic protection, national defense, order protection), citing the inappropriateness of the police, the army, or the state itself."
And further: all this is done according to that method that tries to conceal various political aspirations as a bourgeois initiative, based on the political and party distress of the population.
The emphasis on the civil nature and the form of association, therefore, is not only for the circumvention of legal obstacles that could arise in the course of the registration at the court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor in relations with neighbouring countries.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited in several neighboring states as a potential source of danger, so some ultranationalist politicians of certain neighboring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an individual phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose foundation was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass riots that took place in a neighborhood of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has taken the incidents as an occasion for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the aim of the organization is "national protection".
In their view, in the past 17 years, a real "Gypsy terror" has been felt in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent - according to Political Capital.
Furthermore, the initiative would have started a heavy debate in the Bulgarian public.
As I said, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is also evidenced by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced that they will set up their own guards for resistance purposes.
Since the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far show many similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that the Hungarian Roma will also respond to the threats by organizing their own protection, says Political Capital’s risk warning report.
