Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary holidays are precisely regulated by law, so the practice of re-disposing working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the next year gives us fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as “Holidays”.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and unemployed days.
Work-free days are usually church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
We also celebrate New Year, for example: Both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are days without work - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15th, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23th, commemoration of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, the establishment of the state, on May 1 the work is celebrated, on November 1 and 2 we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each on Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before it, or go to school.
When that day, which falls before or after the holiday, will ultimately be processed, has long been determined by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public employees and public service officials alike.
Except only companies and facilities where the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
Only the holidays at the end of the year make the working rules a little confused: from December 24, life in this country remains formal, as most take the holidays specially suspended for the days between Christmas and New Year’s Eve.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so there will be fewer rearrangements on the working days than this year.
The calendar is first placed around the day of work so that people can stay at home for just four days.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a rest day.
The second rearrangement is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to work out in advance on Friday, October 24th.
The end of the year, however, will be in the sign of the holidays, after everything lies and stands from December 24, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
