Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and delightful cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
On one island, however, you can find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or passing camp of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed from America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered crime in the United States (especially during the prohibition) was seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, over the wide boulevards riding cars, which were one of the worship symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
What about today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
The bar at the Hotel Nacional offers cocktails as desired.
And the cult cars of the fifties run around in Havana to this day, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salt and wet air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, has fallen strongly, nowhere you can find so many wonderful colonial sights in the vicinity as right here.
Other places are being cleaned out, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, there have been new hotels not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba also offers a marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and narrow tracks to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
The most important places are not ignored by the majority of Cuban visitors.
So you don’t have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
Only to mention is that in Hemingway’s previously mentioned estate there is a museum whose visit the one who likes this writer should not be missed.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, protrude steeply from the valley bottom, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, by which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense growth.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of the cigar factories of Havana.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spaniards colonized the island.
Glory and wealth brought her the trade of slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there in the fifties of the last century that would have connected the area with the rest of the land.
This isolation helped to keep it unaware.
Nothing was built there, but nothing was demolished, everyone was happy that they had a roof over their heads.
If you have more than one afternoon time for Trinidad, it is worth looking at interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factorys".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after the darkness, and where the music does not quiet until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba, some call it the most beautiful on the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guantánamo must overcome high and crisp mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
Thanks to the untouched nature of this eastern forepost of Cuba, UNESCO included it in its World Heritage List.
There is the best chocolate made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it is about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the present hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the pig bay and the island of Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, you could write about all these many pages.
But, as you say, it’s better to look with your own eyes.
