For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was brought before a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who was charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name of Muhammad, although any representation of the Islamic prophet is forbidden.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum, was taken home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam according to Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports school leader Robert Boules.
Finally, as the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Surely, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Then the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the image title My Name is Mohammed .
The bear itself did not carry a sign with this name, but the problem is quite simple that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
