A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen’s Nazi archives, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen over a total length of 27 km, could not be viewed until now unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and named, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the US, agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Delicate information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research to be conducted, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health status of forced workers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were against making these named documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The detainee lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
Nothing can be expected to be fundamentally new in these documents, explained Dr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
