Congress approves the MIFID directive, which entered into force on November 1.
Parallel to the parliamentary preparation, which today ended its meeting with the Congress decision in the Senate on the proposals related to the project, the government published the provisions that emerge from the new law, with the intention of enabling the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the Congressional and Senate Members, who had pursued in their negotiations and votes the goal of establishing the best possible regulation that guarantees the safety of investors and regulates the individual entrepreneurial activities in order to ensure a generally efficient market development.
In addition to the modernization of the financial markets, the MIFID, which revises the Investment Services Regulations, is seeking to improve the protection of investors, increase the control claim of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive enables both specialized companies and natural or legal entities to offer financial advice and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS), the advisory firms that cooperate with the investment and intermediary companies of securities.
Furthermore, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions so that the regulatory markets are added to the multilateral systems of effects trading and the systems for the internationalization of trading orders, which would eventually compete with current economic operators.
The law requires investment companies to disclose the priorities of their company profile, confrontation and ways of handling risks in the market and to register all operations carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV’s control.
The Congressional Economic Commission proposed further changes, with the decision that titled bonds must now be considered complex funds for the investor because of their high risk level has been confirmed by the U.S. mortgage and banking crisis.
In addition, the entry into force of the Directive on the Legal Limitation of the Work Areas of Diplomate Economists was used; 30 years after 1977, the Regulation, which restricted the Work Areas reserved for Economists, was adopted.
The Senate, for its part, identified new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the economic mediator, who works on a foreign account, does not require authorization from the CNMV and can offer its services to commercialize products and to attract customers at the same time to several investment companies.
