New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute arose between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) is driven through Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is monitored very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow happens at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit countries in talks," Ukraine's economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] over Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a decline in exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of them remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom supplements its own stockpiles with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
