The State Health Service is expected to carry out checks prior to hiring foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review pre-criminal records, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of the UK.
The principal auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should seek guidelines from the criminal record extract, which assists employers in checking in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel documents, they were not routinely carried out," the report said.
Black said the Scottish health agencies would follow their investigation guidelines highly prior to employment, but added: "Our report highlights areas in which the system can be improved to ensure accurate information about the number of foreign health care workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks in advance of the hiring of potential NHS employees.
“The report says that the NHS Scotland’s current pre-employment tests work well and it is unclear what added value the recommendations will provide,” he said.
Scottish health agencies say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards would have trouble identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation also found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian had been mainly followed.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification controls.
the Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a concern for me to do this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines regarding the pre-employment checks of all employees, including those from abroad, whose release is scheduled next month.
