The climate on Venus could show a glimpse of the future of the Earth
Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft on orbit shows that the planet is even more like a distant twin of Earth than it was previously aware.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and have similar planetary paths, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have prevailed that would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been inhabitable, scientists today believe.
But due to the unbreaked carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by sunlight, and a slower rotation rate, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which studied the plant for a year, offer a soothing look at how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the physics department at the University of Oxford, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said: “It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are pretty similar otherwise.”
“Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus started billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with an inhabitable environment.”
