Is America’s Credit Crisis Instigating the Credit Card Market?
When there is blood in the water, it is only natural that the back flanges whirl around excited.
Now that America’s real estate market is sickening, the predators are targeting the country’s credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of infection from underfunded loans spread to other forms of consumer loans.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both discount rates and expiration rates, which measure the proportion of loans, which are either non-recoverable or more than 30 days too late.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 billion fee from its U.S. consumer funding, partly because of the weakness of credit card holders.
It’s too early to panic.
Losses and losses are still low.
According to the rating agency Moody, the third quarter lapse rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private insolvency laws in 2005 led to a sudden case of bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large part of the losses of kedit cards; the number of applications (and thus exit fees) would again increase whether or not the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
Industry also reports solid rates of payment that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and the confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research company, expects that output volumes in 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: it is more likely that consumers will take up credit card debt, now that home loans are drying out.
However, card issuers look at the cash flow rather than capital values, so falling home prices do not necessarily cause a change in the credit score of the borrower.
They can even be advantageous for card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates decrease when the properties are less worth than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important under the repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexiblely than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
“We will not wake up one day and completely re-evaluate the loans,” says Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden undercovery crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustainable decline are much more real.
If lower home prices and a decrease in credit push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
