Venus is the infernal twin of the earth
Venus is more similar to Earth despite its life-threatening atmosphere than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind turbulences at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected it has flashed on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles reports in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "Ursuppen-Theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms in the ocean are supposed to have stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there was ever life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is probably hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the devil’s twin of the earth, but she is a twin,” Russell said.
Why the Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as no spacecraft had been traveling specifically to explore this planet since the early 1990s.
The latest research, now presented in several "nature" articles, not only emphasizes the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
“They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with the Earth are greater than initially thought,” the Esa said.
In addition to the known wind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of airflows in the earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-tiniest planet in the solar system is almost the same mass as the Earth and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers is almost as large.
The planet, also known as the Morning or Evening Star, circles around the Sun in just 225 days.
But it turns much slower around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar hardly reminds Earth, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
On both was accumulated water, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost into space.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is fixed in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
