The prehistory is embedded, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first “brillo boxes” in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the soap powder “brillo” cardboard boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, exhibited hundreds of cardboard brilliant boxes: These were not (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo Cartonagen factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, merely exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few brilliant wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time were authorized as original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the name "Typ Stockholm" rightly entered art and auction history.
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three of the six museum-owned Brillo boxes from Swedish private ownership, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first foundated and grounded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, however, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press panel with a painter roll without a primer - in addition, it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will have the six boxes in its collection as a copy.
