In the Philippines, rebel troops have surrendered to a hotel in Manila, calling for the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not be responsible for bloodshed, leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Government loyal soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas use.
The nearly two dozen soldiers had been hiding in the building for hours.
Approximately half of them were tried on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly set off with about 30 sympathizers.
The military officers who were supposed to guard him apparently had overrun to him and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces shut down the district around the renowned hotel.
The President called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the action of the soldiers.
“People have enough,” said Trillanes.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the Scout Rangers elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Government critics had called for major demonstrations against the president for Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by allegations of corruption for months.
Manila’s financial district was already the main scene of the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo in 2003.
The insurrection failed after nearly 24 hours of refusal of the army to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes a major shareholder of Versatel
United Internet has secured a share of more than 20 percent in telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday night.
It now holds 20.05 percent of the share capital.
An acquisition had previously been speculated.
The option to increase the share of Versatel is open.
With this step, one wants to advance the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet announced.
Earlier on Wednesday, presumptions had already emerged about an entry after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf network operator by another 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house holds the shares only for a third party, the financial market said.
On the previous day, United Internet had already participated in the mobile company Drillisch with nearly 10 percent.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch placed 17.4 million new shares worth €106.4 million.
United Internet bought 5.15 million shares for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have started talks about marketing cooperation for DSL and mobile products.
“We are strengthening our partnership,” said a United Internet spokesman.
The two companies have founded the joint venture MSP to take over the competitor Freenet.
For the time being, the two companies want to satisfy themselves with a share of about 10 percent of Freenet and do not make use of their right to take over another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet announced Thursday.
However, the two companies kept all options open, in particular to further increase the stake in Freenet AG, it said.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet about a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
The poker around Freenet, which has been ongoing for months and is difficult to understand, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and full-connected customers at the end of the third quarter.
